<div class="callout">
 <div class="callout-label">The Greece number</div>
 <div class="callout-body">Greece is 54.6% dependent on Hormuz for crude petroleum, the highest any covered importer. The value ($8.5B annual) is smaller than China's, but Greek independent refiners are configured around specific Gulf crude grades and have limited ability to substitute quickly. For P&I underwriters with Greek tanker or refinery clients, this is an acute concentration risk at exactly the moment when the disruption is longest.</div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 3 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">Two categories of risk</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">Reroutable at cost, versus structural supply gap. The distinction is not minor.</h2>

<p class="prose">The reroute column in the table above draws a line that matters enormously for risk modelling. For importers who can reroute, Hormuz disruption is a cost event: the Cape of Good Hope adds days and money, but supply eventually arrives. For importers who cannot reroute, it is a supply event: the commodity simply does not reach them through any maritime path, and the response requires overland alternatives, production ramp-up, or demand destruction.</p>

<p class="prose">Brazil and Canada appear in the crude dependency table with significant percentages (24.0% and 14.5% respectively), but both are major domestic oil producers. Their Gulf crude imports reflect refinery grade preferences and specific configuration requirements rather than structural vulnerability. The mitigation path runs through domestic production ramp-up and grade substitution, not tanker rerouting. Argentina's refined petroleum dependency (19.9%) reflects a domestic refining capacity deficit that has no simple maritime fix.</p>

<div class="callout-verdict">
 <div class="callout-verdict-label">The exposure structure at three to four months</div>
 <div class="callout-verdict-body">At the duration the CIA has assessed, the commercial picture separates into three groups. <strong>European crude importers</strong> (Greece, France, Germany) face a cost burden they can finance through the Cape premium and Atlantic alternatives, though at escalating spot prices. <strong>Asian crude importers</strong> (China, Indonesia and others not captured in the current bilateral dataset) face the same cost burden with longer detour distances — 13 days versus 15 — and less refinery flexibility to accept alternative crude grades. <strong>LPG importers across Southeast Asia</strong> can reroute vessels via Cape but face a supply problem that rerouting alone does not solve: Gulf LPG from Qatar and the UAE has no large-scale alternative origin that can be substituted at speed.</div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 4 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The rerouting economics</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">What the Cape diversion costs, vessel class by vessel class, over a 90-day window.</h2>

<p class="prose">For importers who can reroute, the economics are calculable. The Cape of Good Hope adds 12 to 16 days depending on vessel class and origin port. At current market rates (VLCC bunker $55,000 per day, charter $45,000 per day), a single VLCC voyage via Cape costs $1.20 million more than a Hormuz transit in direct vessel costs, plus approximately $197,000 in cargo carrying cost at 5% per annum on a representative $120 million cargo. The total is $1.40 million per voyage.</p>

