<p class="prose">The $480 million figure is the direct fleet rerouting overrun. Bunker plus charter rate plus carrying cost, across all vessel classes over 90 days. It is not the trade value at risk. It is the additional cost imposed on the vessels that are still able to move cargo via an alternative route. The trade value disrupted behind those vessel movements is orders of magnitude larger.</p>

<p class="prose">The detour also extends the liability window. Every additional day a laden VLCC spends at sea is an additional day of P&I exposure on an in-transit cargo. For underwriters writing accumulation on the Cape diversion route, the concentration of diverted tanker traffic around southern Africa during a sustained Hormuz disruption creates its own modelling problem — the same vessels displaced from the Gulf corridor arrive simultaneously at the Cape route.</p>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 5 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">The LPG dimension</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">Five Southeast Asian nations carry a Hormuz exposure that headlines have not reached.</h2>

<p class="prose">Coverage of the disruption has focused almost entirely on crude petroleum and LNG. The LPG exposure in Southeast Asia is structurally significant and has received almost no analytical attention. Thailand is 13.6% dependent on Hormuz for LPG; Indonesia adds 8.2% on top of its 14.7% crude exposure; Vietnam stands at 6.7%; the Philippines at 5.7%; Malaysia at 3.4%. These are bilateral figures from Narrows Tier 1 data; real country-pair trade flows, not corridor allocations.</p>

<div class="callout-red">
 <div class="callout-label">LPG is not crude</div>
 <div class="callout-body">Gulf LPG from Qatar and the UAE flows to Southeast Asian importers aboard purpose-built LPG carriers. Vessels can be rerouted via Cape; the cargo origin cannot be substituted at scale from any non-Gulf source. LPG is a cooking fuel and petrochemical feedstock in these markets. <strong>A supply shortfall in Thailand or the Philippines is not a cost event, it is a domestic energy access event.</strong> The rerouting penalty (Cape, 13–14 days) adds cost but does not resolve the underlying supply question if Gulf LPG export capacity is curtailed at source. These five nations are the most underanalysed Hormuz exposure in the current coverage.</div>
</div>

<hr class="section-rule" />

<!-- SECTION 6 -->
<div class="section-eyebrow">What the bilateral data adds</div>
<h2 class="article-section-title">The headline number cannot tell you who pays. The bilateral data can.</h2>

<p class="prose">The figure that circulates in coverage: "20% of global oil supply transits Hormuz" is correct. But who can use that figure to make any structural decision? It does not tell an accumulation underwriter which of their insured counterparties carries the exposure. It does not tell a crude desk what percentage of their specific supply chain is at risk. It does not tell a lender what a 90-day disruption does to voyage economics across their book.</p>

