<div class="method-note">
 <div class="method-note-label">Methodology and data sources</div>
 <div class="method-note-body">Bilateral dependency figures derived from the Narrows Chokepoint Dependency Simulation Model v0.2 (May 2026). Data source: UN Comtrade 2023 bilateral import data. 17 commodity classes, 51 importing nations, 15 data chokepoints, 8 of which carry bilateral dependency data. Tier 1 bilateral data used for all crude petroleum and LPG figures cited in this analysis. Rerouting cost estimates use representative vessel-class rates: VLCC bunker $55k/day, charter $45k/day, cargo value $120M; Aframax bunker $28k/day, charter $22k/day; Capesize bunker $32k/day, charter $18k/day. Carrying cost at 5% p.a. on representative cargo values. Detour days from Narrows config: VLCC +12d, Aframax +14d, Capesize +13d. In-window voyage estimate: (daily transits × min(90, 20d avg voyage)). Capacity sensitivity score of 1.00 for Hormuz reflects the absence of any navigable bypass for vessels inside the Persian Gulf. Brazil and Canada crude dependency figures reflect bilateral trade data; both countries are major domestic producers and their Gulf crude imports reflect grade preference rather than structural vulnerability — reroute designation reflects supply composition, not vessel diversion. CIA assessment sourced from reporting by The Washington Post, 7 May 2026. All model assumptions are substitutable. Contact fysh@narrows.io to run a scenario against your specific inputs.</div>
